W:Should old acquaintance be forgot
W:and never brought to mind?
W:Should old acquaintance be forgot
W:and old lang syne?
W:
W:For auld lang syne, my dear
W:for auld lang syne
W:we'll take a cup of kindness yet
W:for auld lang syne.
W:
W:And surely you'll buy your pint cup
W:and surely I'll buy mine
W:And we'll take a cup o' kindness yet
W:for auld lang syne.
W:
W:For auld lang syne, my dear
W:for auld lang syne
W:we'll take a cup of kindness yet
W:for auld lang syne.
W:
W:We two have run about the slopes
W:and picked the daisies fine;
W:But we've wandered many a weary foot
W:since auld lang syne.
W:
W:For auld lang syne, my dear
W:for auld lang syne
W:we'll take a cup of kindness yet
W:for auld lang syne.
W:
W:We two have paddled in the stream
W:from morning sun till dine
W:But seas between us broad have roared
W:since auld lang syne.
W:
W:For auld lang syne, my dear
W:for auld lang syne
W:we'll take a cup of kindness yet
W:for auld lang syne.